@node Template "Command Template"

	@{b}COMMAND TEMPLATE@{ub}

Sam must be launched via shell.

It has the command template:

FILE/A,P=PERIOD/N/K,V=VOLUME/N/K,C=CYCLES/N/K,L=LENGTH/N/K,LED/S, R=RANDOM/S,M=MAKELIST/S

@{b}FILE/A@{ub}

The path and filename of any sound-datatype readable sample.

@{b}P=PERIOD/N/K@{ub}

This is the frequency that the sample will be played at.
The smaller the number the 'faster' the sample will be played.

@{b}V=VOLUME/N/K@{ub}

Volume may be between 0 and 64 (default 64).

@{b}C=CYCLES/N/K@{ub}

Cycles sets the amount of times the sample will be played (default 1).

@{b}L=LENGTH/N/K@{ub}

This allows you to set the maximum length of the sample in bytes that will be played.

@{b}LED/S@{ub}

A switch that toggles the audio filter.

@{b}R=RANDOM/S@{ub}

Load a special Sam 'Play List' that contains a list of samples contained within a directory. Then Sam will choose one of these at random and play it. This is an alternative to manually reading the whole directory every time you want to randomly play a sample from a directory.

@{b}M=MAKELIST/S@{ub}

This options enables you to create a special Sam Play List that contains a list of all the files within a directory specified with the FILE/A option. This is used for the 'R=RANDOM/S' command.

If Sam fails to play your sample then it may be because you have a pre V40 datatype library or the sample is an invalid format.
@endnode

@node RandomPlay

	@{b}PLAYING SAMPLES RANDOMLY@{ub}

In order to play samples randomly from a single directory you must first create a list of files.
This is performed from the command line as:

sam dh1:audio/mysamples makelist

or

sam dh1:audio/mysamples m

Sam will scan the directory (no sub-directories) and create a file called '_Sam.List' which contains a list of all the files. This list @{b}must@{ub} be created by Sam!

Then to playback you specify:

sam dh1:audio/mysamples random

or

sam dh1:audio/mysamples r

The method is reasonably simple but just remember to update the List File if you add or delete any samples from the directory. Use the 'm' option again to perform this.

I believe that creating a list file to play samples randomly is the fastest way to choose a file at random, but if anyone knows of a better way then please let me know.
@endnode

@node History "History"

	@{b}History@{ub}

Sam is distributed with the Everyday Organiser package. The following release dates correspond to EO releases.

· @{b}v1.03@{ub} - Sixth Release (1st April 1997)

   - 100% recompiled with SAS/C 6.57.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.02@{ub} - Fourth Release (31st August 1996)

   - No program changes

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.02@{ub} - Third Release (8th June 1996)
   - Program was not releasing a file Lock. This made re-making a list impossible.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.01@{ub} - Second Release (27th March 1996)

